    <ul class="timeline timeline-centered">
      <li class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-info">
          <span>1953-1958</span>
          <p>The visionaries of translation</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3 class="timeline-title">Grace Hopper and FLOW-MATIC</h3>
          <p>
            Grace Hopper initially developed the A-0 system, which functioned more 
            like a linker or loader than a true compiler. However, she continued with her work
            to develop B-0, later known as FLOW-MATIC that was one of the first English-like data
            processing languages. FLOW-MATIC was designed for business applications and readability.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-info">
          <span>1957</span>
          <p>The optimizing compiler takes flight</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3 class="timeline-title">John Backus and FORTRAN</h3>
          <p>
            With hardware getting expensive and human programmers even more so, John Backus led a team at IBM to develop FORTRAN (FORmula TRANslating System). This allowed scientists to write code that looked like algebraic formulas. FORTRAN proved that abstraction did not have to sacrific performance. This effectively launched the field of compiler optimization.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="timeline-item period">
        <div class="timeline-info"></div>
        <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h2 class="timeline-title">The Era of Formalization</h2>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-info">
          <span>1960</span>
          <p>A language to unite all</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3 class="timeline-title"><a href="https://softwarepreservation.computerhistory.org/ALGOL/report/Algol60_report_CACM_1960_June.pdf" target="_blank">ALGOL</a> and BNF</h3>
          <p>
            An international committee of scientists developed ALGOL (ALGOrithmic Language) that became the standard for algorithm description used by the ACM. It introduced code blocks, recursion, and nested function definitions. John Backus introduced the <i>Backus normal form</i>, expanded by Peter Naur for ALGOL 60, and renamed <i>Backus-Naur Form</i> (BNF), a formal way to describe programming language syntax that is still in use today. BNF decouples the <em>definition</em> of a language from its <em>implementation</em>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-info">
          <span>1958-1959</span>
          <p>The Great Divide - Business vs. Science</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3 class="timeline-title">COBOL and Lisp</h3>
          <p>
            COBOL was inspired by FLOW-MATIC and designed for data processing, prioritizing file handling and record management. Its English-like verbose syntax made it self documenting for business managers. In contrast, John McCarthy at MIT created LISP that introduced a radically different paradigm of functional programming. Its homoiconic structure, where code and data share the same representation, enabled powerful metaprogramming capabilities. LISP's design emphasized recursion and higher-order functions, making it a favorite in AI research.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
